ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tumor composed of at least two distinct cellular populations.

Concepts.definition: A neoplasm composed of at least two distinct cellular populations.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Most important; principal.: A benign or malignant neoplasm arising from tissues that do not include fluid areas.  Representative examples include epithelial neoplasms (e.g. lung carcinoma, prostate carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma), and neoplasms arising from the soft tissues and bones (e.g. leiomyosarcoma, liposarcoma, chondrosarcoma, osteosarcoma).  Neoplasms originating from the blood or bone marrow (leukemias and myeloproliferative disorders) are not considered solid tumors.

Concepts.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm arising from tissues that do not include fluid areas.  Representative examples include epithelial neoplasms (e.g. lung carcinoma, prostate carcinoma, breast carcinoma, colon carcinoma), and neoplasms arising from the soft tissues and bones (e.g. leiomyosarcoma, liposarcoma, chondrosarcoma, osteosarcoma).  Neoplasms originating from the blood or bone marrow (leukemias and myeloproliferative disorders) are not considered solid tumors.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Most important; principal.: A benign or malignant neoplasm that contains a single or multiple cystic spaces.  Examples include cystadenoma, mucinous cystadenocarcinoma, and serous cystadenocarcinoma.

Concepts.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm that contains a single or multiple cystic spaces.  Examples include cystadenoma, mucinous cystadenocarcinoma, and serous cystadenocarcinoma.
